[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.10: Multi-Modal Imaging Fusion and Analysis
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.50-8.00 per fusion study
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A radiation oncologist is planning treatment for a brain tumor patient. On her screen she has an MRI showing exquisite soft tissue detail: the tumor's edges, its relationship to critical structures like the optic chiasm and brainstem. She also has a PET scan showing metabolic activity: which parts of the tumor are aggressively growing and which are necrotic. And she has a CT scan showing bone density and electron density data needed to calculate how radiation beams will attenuate through tissue.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each image tells part of the story. None tells the whole story.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Right now, she's doing the fusion in her head. Flipping between three different imaging applications, mentally rotating and overlaying structures, trying to reconcile information presented in different coordinate systems, at different spatial resolutions, acquired on different days when the patient's anatomy may have shifted slightly. This is one of the most cognitively demanding tasks in medicine, and the consequences of getting it wrong are severe: miss the tumor margin and cancer recurs; irradiate too much healthy tissue and the patient loses vision or motor function.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Multi-modal imaging fusion is the process of computationally aligning and combining these different imaging datasets into a unified representation. In radiation oncology alone, treatment planning requires fusing CT (for dose calculation), MRI (for tumor delineation), and often PET (for biological targeting). In surgical planning, neurosurgeons fuse MRI with functional imaging (fMRI) and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) to map eloquent cortex and white matter tracts before cutting. Cardiac surgeons fuse echocardiography with CT angiography. Orthopedic planning fuses MRI with weight-bearing X-rays.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clinical need is enormous. The technical challenge is equally enormous. And the computational infrastructure required to do this at scale, with the accuracy and latency clinicians demand, is a genuinely hard engineering problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Multi-Modal Fusion Works
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What is Image Registration?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At its core, multi-modal fusion is an image registration problem. You have two (or more) images of the same anatomy, acquired with different physics, at different times, possibly in different patient positions. Registration is the process of finding the spatial transformation that maps points in one image to corresponding points in the other.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Think of it like this: if I point to a voxel in the MRI and say "that's the left edge of the tumor," registration tells me which voxel in the CT corresponds to that same physical location in the patient's body.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This sounds straightforward until you realize how many things can differ between acquisitions:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Different coordinate systems.** Each scanner defines its own coordinate origin. The MRI might place (0,0,0) at the center of the magnet bore. The CT might place it at the table reference. The first job is getting both images into a common coordinate frame, usually the patient's anatomical coordinates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Different spatial resolutions.** An MRI might have 1mm isotropic voxels. A PET scan might have 4mm voxels. A CT might have 0.5mm in-plane resolution but 2mm slice thickness. You can't overlay these directly; you need to resample one (or both) to a common grid.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Different fields of view.** The MRI might cover just the head. The CT might cover head and neck. The PET scan might be whole-body. Your fusion needs to handle partial overlap gracefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Non-rigid deformation.** Here's the hard part. The patient's anatomy is not rigid. Between the MRI on Tuesday and the CT on Thursday, the bladder filled, the bowels moved, the patient lost weight, or swelling changed. In the brain, this is less of a problem (the skull constrains things). In the abdomen or pelvis, it's a showstopper for simple rigid registration. You need deformable registration that can model local tissue compression, expansion, and shearing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Registration Methods
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Registration algorithms fall on a spectrum from simple to complex:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rigid registration** uses 6 parameters: three translations and three rotations. It assumes the anatomy is a solid object that moved between scans. Good for brain imaging (skull constraint) and bone-focused applications. Fast, well-understood, and usually the starting point even when you plan to go further.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Affine registration** adds scaling and shearing: 12 parameters. Handles cases where the patient was scanned at slightly different magnifications or where there's a global stretching (positioning differences on the table).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deformable (non-rigid) registration** models local deformations using a dense displacement field. Every voxel gets its own displacement vector. This is what you need for abdominal fusion, where organ motion between scans is substantial. The algorithms are computationally expensive and the results need careful quality control because they can produce physically implausible deformations (folding tissue through itself) if unconstrained.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning registration** is the current frontier. Neural networks (often U-Net variants) are trained on paired images to predict deformation fields directly, without iterative optimization at inference time. This gives you the accuracy of deformable registration with dramatically faster inference (seconds instead of minutes). The tradeoff is that training requires curated datasets of registered image pairs, and generalization to novel anatomy or pathology can be unpredictable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Similarity Metrics: The Multi-Modal Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what makes multi-modal fusion fundamentally harder than registering two images of the same type: the same tissue looks completely different across modalities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In CT, bone is bright (high attenuation). In MRI T1-weighted images, bone is dark (low signal). In PET, bone has variable uptake. You cannot simply compare pixel intensities between a CT and an MRI because the intensity relationship is non-linear and tissue-dependent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Classical solutions include:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Mutual information (MI).** Rather than assuming intensities match, MI measures the statistical dependence between intensity distributions. If two images are well-aligned, knowing the CT intensity at a location should reduce your uncertainty about the MRI intensity at the corresponding location. MI maximization is the standard approach for multi-modal registration and works remarkably well, but it's noisy with local optima that can trap optimization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Normalized cross-correlation (NCC).** Works when there's a local linear relationship between intensities. Faster than MI but makes stronger assumptions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Deep learning similarity.** Train a network to score alignment quality. Can learn modality-specific features that neither MI nor NCC captures. Requires training data of known-good registrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Fusion Strategies: What Happens After Alignment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Once images are in the same coordinate space, you need a strategy for combining information:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Overlay visualization.** The simplest approach: display one modality as a color wash over another. PET-CT fusion typically shows the PET metabolic data as a color overlay on the grayscale CT anatomy. This is a visualization technique, not a computational one, but it's what most clinicians interact with.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Contour propagation.** Draw structures (tumor, organs at risk) on one modality and project them onto others. Critical for radiation therapy planning where the tumor is contoured on MRI but dose must be calculated on CT.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Feature fusion.** Extract quantitative features from each modality and combine them into a unified feature vector per voxel or region. Tumor heterogeneity analysis uses this: combining metabolic features from PET, perfusion features from dynamic contrast MRI, and structural features from anatomical MRI into a single characterization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Joint segmentation.** Use information from all modalities simultaneously to segment structures. A tumor boundary might be ambiguous on CT but clear on MRI; combining both gives a better segmentation than either alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Clinical Context: Where This Matters Most
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Radiation therapy planning** is the highest-volume clinical use case. Every radiation treatment plan requires CT for dose calculation, and the majority benefit from MRI or PET fusion for target definition. This is millions of fusion procedures annually worldwide.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Neurosurgical planning** fuses structural MRI with functional MRI (identifying motor/language cortex) and diffusion tractography (mapping white matter connections). The surgeon needs to know: where is the tumor, where are the critical functions, and what's the safest corridor between them?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cardiac imaging** fuses echocardiography (real-time, inexpensive) with CT or MRI (high spatial resolution, expensive) for interventional planning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Musculoskeletal surgery** fuses MRI (soft tissue) with CT (bone detail) for joint replacement planning and fracture assessment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Ingest DICOM] → [Preprocessing / Standardization] → [Registration Engine] → [Fusion / Overlay] → [Clinical Visualization] → [Treatment Planning Integration]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Ingest DICOM.** Medical images arrive as DICOM (Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine) files from PACS (Picture Archiving and Communication System). Each study may contain hundreds of files representing individual slices. The ingestion layer normalizes metadata, validates completeness, and converts to volumetric arrays.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preprocessing.** Intensity normalization, resampling to a common voxel spacing, skull stripping (for brain), or body segmentation. Each modality has specific preprocessing needs. MRI requires bias field correction (the signal intensity varies with distance from the coil). PET requires SUV (Standardized Uptake Value) normalization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Registration engine.** The computational core. Takes a "fixed" image (typically CT for radiation therapy) and a "moving" image (MRI, PET) and computes the transformation that aligns the moving to the fixed. For clinical use, this must produce results in minutes, not hours. Quality metrics (overlap of known structures, residual distance) validate success.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Fusion and overlay.** Applies the computed transformation to resample the moving image into the fixed image's coordinate space. Generates overlay visualizations, propagates contours, or extracts combined features depending on the clinical application.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical visualization.** DICOM-compliant output that integrates with existing clinical systems. Radiation therapy systems expect specific DICOM objects (DICOM-RT Structure Sets, Registration Objects). Surgical navigation systems have their own format requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Treatment planning integration.** For radiation oncology, the fused dataset feeds directly into the treatment planning system for contouring and dose calculation. This step has strict accuracy requirements: the American Association of Physicists in Medicine recommends spatial accuracy within 2mm for treatment planning fusion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for DICOM storage and staging.** Medical imaging datasets are large (a single CT/MRI/PET study set can be 2-10 GB). S3 provides durable, encrypted, high-throughput object storage for ingesting studies from institutional PACS, staging them for processing, and storing registered outputs. S3's multipart upload handles large DICOM series efficiently, and lifecycle policies manage the transition from hot processing to warm/cold archival.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for registration model hosting.** Deep learning registration models (VoxelMorph, TransMorph, or custom architectures) need GPU inference. SageMaker endpoints provide managed GPU hosting with automatic scaling, model versioning, and A/B testing. For batch processing (e.g., overnight re-registration of a day's studies), SageMaker Processing or Batch Transform handles the workload without maintaining persistent GPU instances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** A fusion workflow has multiple sequential and parallel stages: DICOM validation, preprocessing per modality, registration (possibly multiple pairs), fusion output generation, quality validation, and DICOM export. Step Functions provides visual workflow definition, retry logic, error handling, and audit trails. Each step can invoke different compute backends (Lambda for lightweight tasks, SageMaker for GPU inference, ECS for custom image processing containers).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon ECS (Fargate) for preprocessing containers.** Medical image preprocessing (bias field correction, intensity normalization, resampling, skull stripping) uses specialized libraries (SimpleITK, ANTs, FreeSurfer). These run best in custom containers with specific library versions. Fargate provides serverless container execution without managing the underlying compute.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS HealthImaging for DICOM management.** AWS HealthImaging (formerly Amazon HealthLake Imaging) provides a purpose-built medical imaging store with native DICOM support, sub-second image retrieval, and lossless compression. It integrates with PACS systems for study ingestion and provides API-based access for ML pipelines.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for metadata and tracking.** Tracks study pairs, registration status, quality metrics, and audit information. Each fusion job creates a metadata record linking the input studies, registration parameters, quality scores, and output locations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[PACS / Imaging Archive] -->|DICOM Push\nDICOMweb| B[AWS HealthImaging\nDICOM Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Study notification| C[Step Functions\nFusion Orchestrator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Step 1| D[ECS Fargate\nDICOM Ingest +\nPreprocessing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Preprocessed volumes| E[S3\nProcessing Bucket]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Step 2| F[SageMaker Endpoint\nRegistration Model\nGPU Inference]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Fixed + Moving images| F
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Deformation field +\nRegistered volumes| E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Step 3| G[ECS Fargate\nFusion + QA +\nDICOM Export]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Registered data| G
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Fused DICOM| B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Quality metrics| H[DynamoDB\nFusion Metadata]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|DICOM retrieve| I[Treatment Planning\nSystem / PACS]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Status/metrics| J[CloudWatch\nDashboard + Alarms]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style H fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | AWS HealthImaging, Amazon S3, AWS Step Functions, Amazon SageMaker, Amazon ECS (Fargate), Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `medical-imaging:*` (HealthImaging), `s3:GetObject/PutObject`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `states:StartExecution`, `ecs:RunTask`, `dynamodb:PutItem/GetItem/Query`, `logs:CreateLogGroup/PutLogEvents` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: medical images are PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; HealthImaging: AWS-managed or CMK encryption; SageMaker endpoint: KMS-encrypted volumes; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: all compute in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker, HealthImaging, and CloudWatch Logs. Private subnets for ECS tasks and SageMaker endpoints. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all HealthImaging, S3, and SageMaker API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **GPU Requirements** | SageMaker endpoint: ml.g4dn.xlarge minimum for single-pair registration; ml.g5.2xlarge for production throughput. Batch processing: ml.g4dn.2xlarge instances. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Public datasets: TCIA (The Cancer Imaging Archive) provides multi-modal oncology datasets. BraTS challenge provides matched MRI sequences. Never use real patient images in dev without proper IRB and de-identification. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Per fusion study: ~$0.50 (HealthImaging ingest/retrieve) + ~$1.00-3.00 (SageMaker GPU inference, 30-120 seconds) + ~$0.30 (ECS preprocessing) + ~$0.10 (Step Functions, S3, DynamoDB). Total: $2.50-8.00 depending on complexity and instance size. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS HealthImaging** | DICOM ingestion, storage, and retrieval with native medical imaging support |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Staging bucket for volumetric arrays during processing; archival of registered outputs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-step fusion pipeline with retry logic and error handling |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts GPU-accelerated registration models (VoxelMorph/TransMorph) for inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon ECS (Fargate)** | Runs preprocessing and post-processing containers (SimpleITK, ANTs) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Tracks fusion metadata: study pairs, registration parameters, quality metrics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all storage and compute layers |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics (registration accuracy, latency), alarms (quality failures), dashboards |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-healthlake-imaging-samples`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-healthlake-imaging-samples): Demonstrates AWS HealthImaging import, retrieval, and integration patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-medical-imaging-with-intel-openvino`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-sagemaker-medical-imaging-with-intel-openvino): Medical image inference on SageMaker with optimized frameworks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`guidance-for-multi-modal-data-analysis-with-aws-health-and-ml-services`](https://github.com/aws-solutions-library-samples/guidance-for-multi-modal-data-analysis-with-aws-health-and-ml-services): Multi-modal health data analysis pipeline on AWS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Ingest and validate DICOM studies.** When imaging studies arrive from PACS (either pushed via DICOMweb or pulled by the system), the pipeline must validate that we have matched study pairs suitable for fusion. A radiation therapy case needs at minimum a planning CT and at least one additional modality (MRI or PET). This step confirms that both studies belong to the same patient (matching patient ID), cover overlapping anatomy, and contain complete slice series without gaps. Missing slices or mismatched patients would produce meaningless registration results downstream. The system rejects incomplete or mismatched studies with clear error messages rather than attempting registration on garbage input.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION ingest_and_validate(study_notifications):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Receive notification that new studies are available in HealthImaging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // study_notifications contains metadata: patient ID, modality, study date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // series UIDs, and the HealthImaging datastore/image-set IDs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Group incoming studies by patient to find fusion-eligible pairs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     patient_studies = group study_notifications by patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each patient_id, studies in patient_studies:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check if we have at least two modalities for this patient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         modalities_present = unique set of modality types in studies  // e.g., {"CT", "MR", "PT"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF count(modalities_present) < 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             log "Single modality for patient {patient_id}, skipping fusion"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE  // nothing to fuse
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Identify the fixed image (CT for radiation therapy planning).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         fixed_study = find study where modality == "CT" in studies
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF fixed_study is null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             log "No CT found for patient {patient_id}, cannot proceed with RT fusion"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Identify moving images (MRI, PET, or other modalities to register to CT).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         moving_studies = all studies where modality != "CT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Validate slice completeness for each study.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each study in [fixed_study] + moving_studies:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             slice_count   = count of image frames in study
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             expected      = compute expected slices from slice thickness and coverage
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF slice_count < expected * 0.95:  // allow 5% tolerance for edge slices
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 REJECT study with error "Incomplete series: {slice_count}/{expected} slices"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Create a fusion job record for each CT + moving modality pair.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each moving in moving_studies:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             job_id = generate unique identifier
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             write to metadata store:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 job_id          = job_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 patient_id      = patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 fixed_study_id  = fixed_study.image_set_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 moving_study_id = moving.image_set_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 fixed_modality  = "CT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 moving_modality = moving.modality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 status          = "VALIDATED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 created_at      = current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Trigger the fusion pipeline for this pair.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             start pipeline execution for job_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN list of created job_ids
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Preprocess each modality.** Before registration, each image volume needs modality-specific preprocessing. CT images need Hounsfield unit windowing and potential body segmentation. MRI needs bias field correction (the B1 inhomogeneity that makes signal brighter near the coil and darker at the center) and intensity normalization. PET needs SUV calculation from raw counts using patient weight and injection activity. All modalities get resampled to a common voxel spacing and converted from DICOM slice stacks to 3D volumetric arrays. Skip bias field correction on MRI and your registration will be biased by the artifact; skip SUV normalization on PET and your quantitative analysis is meaningless.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_study(study_id, modality, target_spacing):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Retrieve the DICOM frames from HealthImaging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This returns raw pixel data + metadata for each slice.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     dicom_frames = retrieve all frames for study_id from HealthImaging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Convert DICOM slice stack to a 3D volumetric array.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Sorts slices by position, handles varying slice thickness,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // and creates a regular 3D grid with correct spatial orientation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     volume, affine_matrix = assemble_volume_from_dicom(dicom_frames)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // affine_matrix encodes the mapping from voxel indices to physical coordinates (mm).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply modality-specific preprocessing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF modality == "CT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // CT values are already in Hounsfield units (HU).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Clip to a clinically relevant range to remove scanner artifacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume = clip(volume, min=-1024, max=3071)  // standard HU range
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Optionally segment body from air/table for registration efficiency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body_mask = threshold_body_segmentation(volume, threshold=-300)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF modality == "MR":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // MRI bias field correction: removes the smooth intensity gradient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // caused by RF coil proximity effects. Without this, the same tissue
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // type has different intensities at different locations, which confuses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // registration similarity metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume = n4_bias_field_correction(volume)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Intensity normalization: scale to [0, 1] range using percentile clipping.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Percentiles avoid outlier influence from artifact voxels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         p1, p99 = percentile(volume, [1, 99])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume = clip(volume, p1, p99)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume = (volume - p1) / (p99 - p1)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF modality == "PT":  // PET
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Convert raw counts to Standardized Uptake Values (SUV).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // SUV = (activity concentration) / (injected dose / patient weight)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // This makes values comparable across patients and scanners.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_weight   = get from DICOM metadata (kg)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         injected_dose    = get from DICOM metadata (Bq)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume = compute_suv(volume, patient_weight, injected_dose)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Resample to target isotropic spacing for registration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Registration works best when both images have the same voxel dimensions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Typical target: 1mm isotropic for brain, 2mm for body.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     volume_resampled, new_affine = resample_to_spacing(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         volume, affine_matrix, target_spacing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save preprocessed volume to S3 for the registration step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     output_path = "s3://processing-bucket/{study_id}/preprocessed.nii.gz"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_nifti(volume_resampled, new_affine, output_path)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN output_path, new_affine
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Compute registration (align moving to fixed).** This is the computational core. The registration model takes the fixed image (CT) and moving image (MRI or PET) and computes a spatial transformation that aligns them. For rigid registration (brain), this is 6 parameters. For deformable registration (body), this is a dense displacement field with a displacement vector at every voxel. The deep learning approach (VoxelMorph-style networks) computes deformable registration in seconds on a GPU, compared to minutes or hours for traditional iterative optimization. The output is both the deformation field (which can be applied to any additional images or contours in the moving image's space) and the registered moving image resampled into the fixed image's coordinate system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION register_images(fixed_path, moving_path, registration_type):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load preprocessed volumes from S3.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     fixed_volume  = load_nifti(fixed_path)   // e.g., CT volume
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     moving_volume = load_nifti(moving_path)  // e.g., MRI volume
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF registration_type == "rigid":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Rigid registration: 6 degrees of freedom (3 translation, 3 rotation).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Appropriate for brain imaging where the skull constrains deformation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Uses mutual information as similarity metric (handles cross-modal intensities).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         transformation = rigid_registration(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             fixed  = fixed_volume,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             moving = moving_volume,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             metric = "mutual_information",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             optimizer = "gradient_descent",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             multi_resolution_levels = 3  // coarse-to-fine for robustness
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Apply rigid transform to moving image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         registered_moving = apply_rigid_transform(moving_volume, transformation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deformation_field = null  // rigid has no dense deformation field
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF registration_type == "deformable":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Step A: Start with rigid alignment as initialization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Deformable registration needs a good starting point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         initial_transform = rigid_registration(fixed_volume, moving_volume,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                                metric="mutual_information")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         aligned_moving = apply_rigid_transform(moving_volume, initial_transform)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Step B: Deep learning deformable registration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Invoke the SageMaker-hosted model (VoxelMorph or TransMorph architecture).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The model predicts a dense displacement field in a single forward pass (no iteration).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_input = prepare_model_input(fixed_volume, aligned_moving)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         inference_result = invoke_sagemaker_endpoint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             endpoint_name = "registration-model-endpoint",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             payload       = model_input
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         deformation_field = inference_result.displacement_field
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // deformation_field shape: (H, W, D, 3) giving dx, dy, dz displacement per voxel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Step C: Apply deformation field to get registered moving image.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         registered_moving = warp_volume(aligned_moving, deformation_field)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Compute registration quality metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     quality = compute_quality_metrics(fixed_volume, registered_moving)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // quality includes: mutual_information, dice_overlap (if landmarks available),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // target_registration_error (if fiducials available), jacobian_determinant_stats
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (checks for folding/implausible deformations).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save outputs to S3.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_nifti(registered_moving, "s3://processing-bucket/{job_id}/registered_moving.nii.gz")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF deformation_field is not null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         save_array(deformation_field, "s3://processing-bucket/{job_id}/deformation_field.npy")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN registered_moving, deformation_field, quality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Validate registration quality.** A registration that looks plausible can still be subtly wrong, and in treatment planning a 3mm error means irradiating the wrong tissue. This step applies automated quality checks before accepting the result. The Jacobian determinant of the deformation field identifies physically implausible regions (negative Jacobian means tissue folded through itself, which is not biologically possible). Overlap metrics on automatically segmented structures (brain, skull base landmarks) quantify alignment accuracy. If quality fails thresholds, the system routes to a medical physicist for manual review rather than silently passing bad registration downstream. The quality gate is not optional; it's the safety mechanism.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION validate_registration_quality(job_id, fixed_volume, registered_moving, deformation_field):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     quality_report = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     passed = true
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check 1: Mutual information between fixed and registered moving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Higher MI means better statistical alignment between the two images.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     mi_score = compute_mutual_information(fixed_volume, registered_moving)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     quality_report["mutual_information"] = mi_score
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF mi_score < MI_THRESHOLD:  // typically 1.0-1.5 for well-registered cross-modal pairs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         passed = false
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["mi_failure"] = "MI below threshold: possible misregistration"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check 2: Jacobian determinant analysis (deformable only).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The Jacobian determinant at each voxel tells you the local volume change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // det(J) = 1 means no volume change (pure displacement).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // det(J) > 1 means local expansion. det(J) < 1 means compression.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // det(J) <= 0 means the deformation is folding (physically impossible).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF deformation_field is not null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         jacobian = compute_jacobian_determinant(deformation_field)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         folding_fraction = fraction of voxels where jacobian <= 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["folding_fraction"] = folding_fraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["jacobian_min"]     = min(jacobian)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["jacobian_max"]     = max(jacobian)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF folding_fraction > 0.001:  // more than 0.1% folding voxels
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             passed = false
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_report["jacobian_failure"] = "Excessive folding detected"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check 3: Landmark-based target registration error (if available).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If anatomical landmarks were identified in both images, measure
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the residual distance between corresponding landmarks after registration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     landmarks = get_automatic_landmarks(fixed_volume, registered_moving)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF landmarks is not null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         tre = compute_target_registration_error(landmarks)  // in mm
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["mean_tre_mm"] = mean(tre)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_report["max_tre_mm"]  = max(tre)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF mean(tre) > 3.0:  // AAPM recommends < 2mm; 3mm is our alert threshold
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             passed = false
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_report["tre_failure"] = "Mean TRE exceeds 3mm"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update metadata with quality results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update metadata store for job_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_metrics = quality_report
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_passed  = passed
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status          = "QA_PASSED" if passed else "QA_FAILED_REVIEW_NEEDED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF not passed:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Route to medical physicist for manual review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         send_notification(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             queue  = "physics-review-queue",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             job_id = job_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reason = quality_report
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN passed, quality_report
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Generate fused output and export to clinical systems.** Once registration passes quality checks, the system generates the clinical deliverables. For radiation therapy, this means creating DICOM Registration Objects (encoding the spatial transformation), resampled image series (the MRI/PET in CT coordinate space), and optionally fused overlay series for visual review. The outputs must be DICOM-compliant to flow back into PACS and treatment planning systems. This step also generates summary visualizations (checkerboard patterns, color overlays) that clinicians use to visually verify alignment before relying on it for treatment decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION generate_fusion_output(job_id, fixed_volume, registered_moving, 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                  deformation_field, fixed_metadata, moving_metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate DICOM Spatial Registration object.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This encodes the transformation so treatment planning systems can apply it
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // to any additional data (contours, dose distributions) without re-registering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     registration_dicom = create_dicom_registration_object(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         fixed_frame_of_reference  = fixed_metadata.frame_of_reference_uid,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         moving_frame_of_reference = moving_metadata.frame_of_reference_uid,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         transformation            = deformation_field or rigid_transform,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         registration_method       = "deep_learning_deformable"  // or "rigid"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate resampled DICOM series (moving modality in fixed coordinate space).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This is what clinicians will view overlaid with the CT in treatment planning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     resampled_series = create_dicom_series(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pixel_data         = registered_moving,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reference_metadata = fixed_metadata,  // inherit geometry from fixed (CT)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         modality           = moving_metadata.modality,  // preserve original modality label
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         series_description = "Registered {moving_modality} to CT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate visual QA outputs for clinical review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Checkerboard: alternating tiles from fixed and registered moving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Reveals misalignment at tile boundaries.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     checkerboard = generate_checkerboard(fixed_volume, registered_moving, tile_size=32)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Color overlay: fixed as grayscale base, registered moving as color wash.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     color_overlay = generate_color_overlay(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         base    = fixed_volume,       // grayscale CT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         overlay = registered_moving,  // colored MRI or PET
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         alpha   = 0.4                 // transparency level
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store DICOM outputs back to HealthImaging for PACS retrieval.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     store_to_healthimaging(registration_dicom)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     store_to_healthimaging(resampled_series)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Save QA visualizations to S3 (PNG/NIFTI for review dashboards).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_visualization(checkerboard, "s3://processing-bucket/{job_id}/qa_checkerboard.png")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     save_visualization(color_overlay, "s3://processing-bucket/{job_id}/qa_overlay.png")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Final metadata update.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     update metadata store for job_id:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status                   = "COMPLETED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output_registration_uid  = registration_dicom.sop_instance_uid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output_series_uid        = resampled_series.series_instance_uid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         completed_at             = current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         registration_object: registration_dicom.sop_instance_uid,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         resampled_series:    resampled_series.series_instance_uid,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         qa_visualizations:   [checkerboard_path, overlay_path]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
